    L06_P1_p1: "New Japanese banknotes will be issued in 2024. This will be the first redesign since 2004.",
    L06_P1_p2: "In Japan, the first modern banknote with a portrait was issued in 1881. Since then, 17 people’s portraits have appeared on Japanese banknotes. Prince Shotoku has appeared most frequently. Nowadays, the portraits are chosen from famous figures from the Meiji period or later.",
    L06_P1_p3: "The reason why portraits are used on banknotes is to prevent counterfeiting. It is said that human eyes can recognize small changes in human faces. Therefore, portraits based on detailed photographs became common.",
    L06_P1_full: "New Japanese banknotes will be issued in 2024. This will be the first redesign since 2004.<br><br>In Japan, the first modern banknote with a portrait was issued in 1881. Since then, 17 people’s portraits have appeared on Japanese banknotes. Prince Shotoku has appeared most frequently. Nowadays, the portraits are chosen from famous figures from the Meiji period or later.<br><br>The reason why portraits are used on banknotes is to prevent counterfeiting. It is said that human eyes can recognize small changes in human faces. Therefore, portraits based on detailed photographs became common.",

    L06_P2_p1: "Three historical figures have been selected for the new designs. All of them spent time abroad, learned about foreign cultures, and gained the latest knowledge at that time. They became pioneers in their fields in Japan and used their experiences to help create a modern nation.",
    L06_P2_p2: "Kitasato Shibasaburo is known as the father of modern medicine in Japan. He saw many people die from infectious diseases. He thought it possible that doctors could prevent such diseases. He studied in Germany and developed a way to save patients from tetanus and diphtheria. Prestigious universities abroad offered him a position, but he returned to Japan to devote his life to the country.",
    L06_P2_full: "Three historical figures have been selected for the new designs. All of them spent time abroad, learned about foreign cultures, and gained the latest knowledge at that time. They became pioneers in their fields in Japan and used their experiences to help create a modern nation.<br><br>Kitasato Shibasaburo is known as the father of modern medicine in Japan. He saw many people die from infectious diseases. He thought it possible that doctors could prevent such diseases. He studied in Germany and developed a way to save patients from tetanus and diphtheria. Prestigious universities abroad offered him a position, but he returned to Japan to devote his life to the country.",

    L06_P3_p1: "Tsuda Umeko is known as a pioneer of female education in Japan. At the age of six, she was selected to study in the United States. Eleven years later, she returned to Japan. Soon, she found Japanese women had few opportunities in education or jobs. She felt it necessary to improve their social status. In 1900, she founded a school that later became one of the first universities for women in Japan.",
    L06_P3_p2: "Shibusawa Eiichi is regarded as the father of Japanese capitalism. He went to Paris for the 1867 World Exhibition and visited several European countries. He learned about Western social and economic systems there. After returning to Japan, he helped create the first bank and hundreds of leading companies. He also supported education, international relationships, and public welfare.",
    L06_P3_full: "Tsuda Umeko is known as a pioneer of female education in Japan. At the age of six, she was selected to study in the United States. Eleven years later, she returned to Japan. Soon, she found Japanese women had few opportunities in education or jobs. She felt it necessary to improve their social status. In 1900, she founded a school that later became one of the first universities for women in Japan.<br><br>Shibusawa Eiichi is regarded as the father of Japanese capitalism. He went to Paris for the 1867 World Exhibition and visited several European countries. He learned about Western social and economic systems there. After returning to Japan, he helped create the first bank and hundreds of leading companies. He also supported education, international relationships, and public welfare.",

    L06_P4_p1: "Redesigning banknotes may encourage Japan to go cashless faster. It costs companies a lot of money to adjust equipment to use new banknotes. Moreover, the working population is decreasing because of the low birthrate in Japan. A cashless system saves a lot of work by making transactions easier. It also makes it convenient for foreign tourists to visit Japan, since they don’t need to exchange currencies.",
    L06_P4_p2: "Some countries stopped issuing their largest banknotes to go cashless. Maybe Japan should have abolished the ¥10,000 banknote. If there were no ¥10,000 banknotes, it would be much easier to carry one card or one smartphone instead of many small banknotes.",
    L06_P4_full: "Redesigning banknotes may encourage Japan to go cashless faster. It costs companies a lot of money to adjust equipment to use new banknotes. Moreover, the working population is decreasing because of the low birthrate in Japan. A cashless system saves a lot of work by making transactions easier. It also makes it convenient for foreign tourists to visit Japan, since they don’t need to exchange currencies.<br><br>Some countries stopped issuing their largest banknotes to go cashless. Maybe Japan should have abolished the ¥10,000 banknote. If there were no ¥10,000 banknotes, it would be much easier to carry one card or one smartphone instead of many small banknotes.",

